N/L2T.name: (amount of substance per time) per area

%.name: percent
%.description:
Parts per hundred. 
				This is one of the few symbols which can be used with multiple unit classes. 
				It can be used with each class that represent a ratio of like quantities (e.g., mass per mass).

ppk.name: part per thousand
ppk.description: A ratio of values divided by 1000 where the original values were in the same units.

ppm.name: part per million
ppm.description: A ratio of values divided by 1E6 where the original values were in the same units.

Euc.name: euclid
Euc.description:
A dimensionless unit of proportion, named after the Greek mathematician, Euclid. 
				It represents the SI implied unit of "1" which is sometimes called a "dimensionless derived unit".

bit.name: bit
bit.description:
A bit (a contraction of binary digit) is the basic unit of information in computing and 
				telecommunications. 
				A bit can have only two values: either 1 or 0.

%[mass].name: percent [mass basis]
%[mass].description:
The percent of mass relative to mass. 
				That is, mass divided by mass divided 100 where the original mass values were in the same units.

ppm[mass].name: part per million [mass basis]
ppm[mass].description:
The parts per million of mass relative to mass. 
				That is, mass divided by mass divided by 1E6 where the original mass values were in the same units.

%[vol].name: percent [volume basis]
%[vol].description:
The percent of volume relative to volume That is, volume divided by volume divided by 100 where the 
				original volume values were in the same units.

ppm[vol].name: part per million [volume basis]
ppm[vol].description:
The parts per million of volume relative to volume That is, volume divided by volume divided by 1E6 
				where the original volume values were in the same units.

(m3/d)/(m3/d).name: (cubic metre per day) per (cubic metre per day)

1E6 (ft3/d)/(bbl/d).name: (million cubic foot per day) per (barrel per day)

(m3/s)/(m3/s).name: (cubic metre per second) per (cubic metre per second)

0.001 gal[UK]/gal[UK].name: UK gallon per thousand UK gallon

0.001 gal[US]/ft3.name: US gallon per thousand cubic foot

0.001 gal[US]/gal[US].name: US gallon per thousand US gallon

1000 m3/m3.name: thousand cubic metre per cubic metre

1E6 ft3/(acre.ft).name: million cubic foot per acre foot

Mibyte.name: mebibyte
Mibyte.description:
1048576 bytes. 
				Commonly called a megabyte but mega refers to powers of ten rather than powers of two.

m3/(m3.deltaK).name: cubic metre per cubic metre delta kelvin

1E-6 m3/(m3.deltaC).name: (cubic metre per million cubic metre) per delta Celsius

1E-6 m3/(m3.deltaF).name: (cubic metre per million cubic metre) per delta Fahrenheit

ppm[vol]/deltaC.name: (part per million [volume basis]) per delta Celsius

ppm[vol]/deltaF.name: (part per million [volume basis)] per delta Fahrenheit

cu.name: capture unit
cu.description:
The macroscopic capture cross section is the sum of all the various weighted elemental capture cross 
				sections. 
				The are "1E-3 cm2/cm3" often referred to as capture unit (c.u.) or sigma unit (s.u.). 
				(Adapted from Ransom, Robert C," Practical Formation Evaluation", New York: J Wiley, 1995.)

Ci.name: curie
Ci.description:
The Curie (symbol Ci) is a non-SI unit of radioactivity, named after Marie and Pierre Curie. 
				It is defined as 3.7E10 decays per second. 
				The SI derived unit of radioactivity is the becquerel (Bq), which equates to one decay per second.

Bd.name: baud
Bd.description:
The baud rate is the number of distinct symbols transmitted per second, that is, the number of times 
				per second the signal carrying the communication varies in strength or frequency. 
				If the symbols transmitted have only two states (on or off) then the baud rate is the same as the 
				transmission rate in bits per second. 
				(Adapted from Russ Rowlett's "A Dictionary of Units of Measurement" at http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/)

Bq.name: becquerel
Bq.description: The activity of a radionuclide decaying at the rate of one spontaneous nuclear transition per second

Hz.name: hertz
Hz.description: The frequency of a periodic phenomenon of which the period is 1 second.

bit/s.name: bit per second
bit/s.description: A unit of transmission speed, equal to one bit per second.

m3/(s.m3).name: cubic metre per time cubic metre

rad.name: radian
rad.description:
The radian is the plane angle between two radii of a circle that cut of, on the circumference,an arc 
				equal in length to the radius.

cgr.name: centesimal-minute
cgr.description: One hundredth of a centesimal degree (also known as grad, grade or gon)

dega.name: angular degree
dega.description: 1/360 of a full circle = PI /180 radians

gon.name: gon
gon.description: 1/400 of a turn (full circle). Also known as gradian, grad, or grade.

mila.name: angular mil
mila.description: Angle subtended by 1/6400 part of a circle.

deltaC.name: delta Celsius
deltaC.description:
Change in degree Celsius. 
				The degree Celsius and the kelvin are equal in size, so that the numerical value of a temperature 
				difference or temperature interval is the same when expressed in either degrees Celsius or in 
				kelvins (because the offset cancels). 
				For temperature intervals rather than specific temperatures, 1 deltaF = 1 deltaR = 5/9 deltaC = 5/9 deltaK.

deltaF.name: delta Fahrenheit
deltaF.description:
Change in degrees Fahrenheit. 
				Kelvin=(Fahrenheit + 459.67) x 5/9 so a difference in Fahrenheit temperature cancels out the 459.67 
				offset. 
				For temperature intervals rather than specific temperatures, 1 deltaF = 1 deltaR = 5/9 deltaC = 5/9 deltaK.

deltaR.name: delta Rankine
deltaR.description:
Change in degrees Rankine. 
				Rankine = (Celsius + 273.15) x 9/5 so a difference in Fahrenheit temperature cancels out the 273.15 
				offset. 
				For temperature intervals rather than specific temperatures, 1 deltaF = 1 deltaR = 5/9 deltaC = 5/9 deltaK.

deltaK.name: delta kelvin
deltaK.description:
Change in kelvin. 
				A zero difference in Kelvin temperature is not the same as being at zero on the Kelvin temperature 
				scale. 
				The degree Celsius and the kelvin are equal in size, so that the numerical value of a temperature 
				difference or temperature interval is the same when expressed in either degrees Celsius or in kelvins.

deltaC.m2.h/kcal[th].name: delta Celsius square metre hour per thousand calory

deltaF.ft2.h/Btu[IT].name: delta Fahrenheit square foot hour per BTU

deltaK.m2/kW.name: delta kelvin square metre per kilowatt

deltaK.m2/W.name: delta kelvin square metre per watt

A.name: ampere
A.description:
The ampere is that constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of 
				infinite length, of negligible circular cross section, and placed 1 metre apart in vacuum, would 
				produce between these conductors a force equal to 2 x 10**-7 newton per metre of length.

Oe.name: oersted
Oe.description:
1 Oe corresponds to (1000/(4*pi)) A/m. 
				This unit is part of the so-called electromagnetic three-dimensional CGS system and cannot strictly 
				speaking be compared to the corresponding SI unit, which has four dimensions when only mechanical 
				and electric quantities are considered.

S.name: siemens
S.description:
The electric conductance of a conductor in which a current of 1 A is produced by an electric 
				potential difference of 1 V. 
				Also known as a mho.

F.name: farad
F.description:
The capacitance of a capacitor between the plates of which there appears a difference of potential 
				of 1 V when it is charged by a quantity of electricity equal to 1 C.

C.name: coulomb
C.description: The time integral of electric current, equal to 1 A.s

cd.name: candela
cd.description:
The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic 
				radiation of frequency 540 X 10**12 hertz and that has a radian intensity in that direction of 1/683 
				watt per steradian.

lm.name: lumen
lm.description: The luminous flux emitted in a solid angle of 1 sr by a point source having a uniform intensity of 1 cd.

lx.name: lux
lx.description: The illuminance produced by a luminous flux of 1 lm uniformly distributed over a surface of 1 m2.

footcandle.name: footcandle
footcandle.description:
A unit of illuminance on a surface that is everywhere one foot from a uniform point source of light 
				of one candle and equal to one lumen per square foot (from www.merriam-webster.com). 
				To convert to Lux, convert the square foot component to square meter (i.e., 1/( 0.3048)**2).

K.name: degree kelvin
K.description:
The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic 
				temperature of the triple point of water.

m.name: metre
m.description:
The metre is the length equal to 1 650 763.73 wavelengths in vacuum of the radiation corresponding 
				to the transition between the levels 2p10 and 5d5 of the krypton-86 atom. 
				In the US, this is called a meter.

angstrom.name: angstrom
angstrom.description:
The angstrom is widely used by x-ray crystallographers and structural chemists because all chemical 
				bonds lie in the range 1 to 3 angstroms.

chain.name: chain
chain.description: international chain equal to 22 international yards or 66 international feet. From EPSG.

chain[US].name: US survey chain
chain[US].description: 66 US survey feet (exactly). Also called Gunter's chain. From NIST-44.

ft[BnA].name: British foot [Benoit 1895 A]
ft[BnA].description:
Uses Benoit's 1895 British yard-metre ratio as given by Clark as 0.9143992 metre.s per yard. 
				Used for deriving metric size of ellipsoid in Palestine.

ft[BnB].name: British foot [Benoit 1895 B]
ft[BnB].description:
Uses Benoit's 1895 British yard-metre ratio as given by Bomford as 39.370113 inches per metre. 
				Used in West Malaysian mapping.

ft[Br36].name: British foot [1936]
ft[Br36].description:
For the 1936 retriangulation OSGB defines the relationship of 10 feet of 1796 to the International 
				metre through the logarithmic relationship (10^0.48401603 exactly). 
				1 ft = 0.3048007491...m. 
				Also used for metric conversions in Ireland.

ft[Br65].name: British foot [1865]
ft[Br65].description:
Uses Clark's estimate of 1853-1865 British foot-metre ratio of 0.9144025 metres per yard. 
				Used in 1962 and 1975 estimates of Indian foot.

ft[Cla].name: Clarke foot
ft[Cla].description:
Assumes Clarke's 1865 ratio of 1 British foot = 0.3047972654 French legal metres applies to the 
				international metre.

ft[GC].name: Gold Coast foot
ft[GC].description:
Used in Ghana and some adjacent parts of British west Africa prior to metrication, except for the 
				metrication of projection defining parameters when British foot (Sears 1922) used.

ft[Ind].name: indian foot
ft[Ind].description:
Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). 
				British yard (= 3 British feet) taken to be J.S.Clark's 1865 value of 0.9144025 metres.

ft[Ind37].name: indian foot [1937]
ft[Ind37].description:
Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). 
				British foot taken to be 1895 Benoit value of 12/39.370113m. 
				Rounded to 8 decimal places as 0.30479841. 
				Used from Bangladesh to Vietnam. 
				Previously used in India and Pakistan but superseded.

ft[Ind62].name: indian foot ]1962]
ft[Ind62].description:
Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). 
				British yard (3 feet) taken to be J.S. 
				Clark's 1865 value of 0.9144025m. 
				Rounded to 7 significant figures with a small error as 1 Ind ft=0.3047996m. 
				Used in Pakistan since metrication.

ft[Ind75].name: indian foot [1975]
ft[Ind75].description:
Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). 
				British yard (3 feet) taken to be J.S. 
				Clark's 1865 value of 0.9144025m. 
				Rounded to 7 significant figures as 1 Ind ft=0.3047995m. 
				Used in India since metrication.

ft[Se].name: British foot [Sears 1922]
ft[Se].description:
Uses Sear's 1922 British yard-metre ratio as given by Bomford as 39.370147 inches per metre. 
				Used in East Malaysian and older New Zealand mapping.

ft[SeT].name: British foot [Sears 1922 truncated]
ft[SeT].description:
Uses Sear's 1922 British yard-metre ratio (UoM code 9040) truncated to 6 significant figures; this 
				truncated ratio (0.914398, UoM code 9099) then converted to other imperial units. 
				3 ftSe(T) = 1 ydSe(T).

link[US].name: US survey link
link[US].description: US survey link. Equal to 0.66 US survey foot (exactly).

mi[naut].name: international nautical mile
mi[naut].description:
The nautical mile is a special unit employed for marine and aerial navigation to express distance. 
				The unit was originally chosen, and continues to be used, because one nautical mile on the surface 
				of the Earth subtends approximately one minute of angle at the centre of the Earth, which is 
				convenient when latitude and longitude are measured in degrees and minutes of angle.

mi[nautUK].name: United Kingdom nautical mile
mi[nautUK].description:
The Imperial (UK) nautical mile, also known as the Admiralty mile, was defined in terms of the knot, 
				such that one nautical mile was exactly 6,080 international feet (1,853.184 m):[6] it was abandoned 
				in 1970[6] and, for legal purposes, old references to the obsolete unit are now converted to 1,853 
				metres exactly.

mi[US].name: US survey mile
mi[US].description: United States survey mile is 5280 feet survey (exactly). From NIST-55.

knot.name: knot
knot.description: The knot is defined as one nautical mile per hour.

m3/(s.m2).name: cubic metre per second square metre

ft3/(min.ft2).name: cubic foot per minute square foot

ft3/(s.ft2).name: cubic foot per second square foot

gal[UK]/(h.ft2).name: UK gallon per hour square foot

gal[UK]/(h.in2).name: UK gallon per hour square inch

gal[UK]/(min.ft2).name: UK gallon per minute square foot

gal[US]/(h.ft2).name: US gallon per hour square foot

gal[US]/(h.in2).name: US gallon per hour square inch

gal[US]/(min.ft2).name: US gallon per minute square foot

Gal.name: galileo
Gal.description: The gal is employed in geodesy and geophysics to express acceleration due to gravity.

gn.name: gravity
gn.description: The standard acceleration due to gravity on Earth.

TD[API].name: teradarcy-API
TD[API].description: The API teradarcy is numerically equal to a metre squared.

acre.name: acre
acre.description: US survey acre. Equal to 43,560 square survey foot (exactly). From NIST.

b.name: barn
b.description: The barn is a unit of area employed to express cross sections in nuclear physics.

section.name: section
section.description: 640 acres or 1 square US survey mile.

D.name: darcy
D.description:
The darcy is a unit for expressing the permeability of porous solids, not area (from NIST-SI). 
				One darcy is the permeability of a solid through which one cubic centimeter of fluid, having a 
				viscosity of one centipoise, will flow in one second through a section one centimeter thick and one 
				square centimeter in cross section, if the pressure difference between the two sides of the solid is 
				one atmosphere (from Russ Rowlett's "A Dictionary of Units of Measurement" at 
				http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/). 
				Thus, 1 D=(1 cm3)(1 cP)/((1 s)(1 cm2)(1 atm/cm))=1 cm.cP/(atm.s/cm)=1 cm2.cP/atm.s=(1E-4 m2)(1E-3 
				Pa.s)/(1.01325E5 Pa.s)=1E-12/1.01325 m2 [exactly]. 
				Also see, Wangen, Magnus (2010) Physical Principles of Sedimentary Basin Analysis (page 12), 
				Cambridge, UK New York: Cambridge University Press, 2010. 
				ISBN 978-0-511-71237-1.

D[API].name: darcy-API
D[API].description:
The darcy is a unit of permeability in fluid flow through a porous medium, having the dimensions of 
				dynamic viscosity multiplied by volume flowrate per unit area and divided by pressure gradient, 
				which simplifies to a dimension of area. 
				A darcy is defined as being exactly equal to 1 um2. 
				A permeability of one darcy will permit a flow of 1 m3/s of fluid of 1 Pa.s viscosity through an 
				area of 1 m2 under a pressure gradient of 10**12 Pa/m.

kcal[th]/(kg.deltaC).name: thousand calorie per kilogram delta Celsius

kW.h/(kg.deltaC).name: kilowatt hour per kilogram delta Celsius

St.name: stokes
St.description: The stokes is the CGS unit for kinematic viscosity.

mol.m2/(mol.s).name: mole square metre per mole second

Pa.s.m3/kg.name: pascal second square metre per kilogram

W.m2.deltaK/(J.deltaK).name: watt square metre delta kelvin per joule delta kelvin

1000 ft3/(d.ft).name: (thousand cubic foot per day) per foot

1000 m3/(d.m).name: (thousand cubic metre per day) per metre

1000 m3/(h.m).name: (thousand cubic metre per hour) per metre

rd.name: rad
rd.description:
A obsolete unit of absorbed radiation dose. 
				It was originally defined in CGS units in 1953 as the dose causing 100 ergs of energy to be absorbed 
				by one gram of matter. 
				It has been replaced by the gray in most of the world.

Gy.name: gray
Gy.description: The absorbed dose when the energy per unit mass imparted to matter by ionizing radiation is 1 J/kg

Sv.name: sievert
Sv.description:
The dose equivalent when the absorbed dose of ionizing radiation multiplied by the dimensionless 
				factors Q (quality factor) and N (product of any of the multiplying factors) stipulated by the 
				International Commission on Radiological Protection is 1.0 J/kg.

rem.name: rem
rem.description:
A unit of radiation dosage (such as from X rays) applied to humans. 
				Derived from the phrase Roentgen equivalent man, the rem is now defined as the dosage in rads that 
				will cause the same amount of biological injury as one rad of X rays or gamma rays.

Sv/s.name: sievert per second
Sv/s.description:
The dose equivalent rate when the absorbed dose per second of ionizing radiation multiplied by the 
				appropriate factors is equivalent to 1 Sievert per second.

H.name: henry
H.description:
The inductance of a closed circuit in which an electromotive force of 1 V is produced when the 
				electric current in the circuit varies uniformly at a rate of 1 A/s.

ohm.name: ohm
ohm.description:
The electric resistance between two points of a conductor when a constant difference of potential of 
				1 V, applied between these two points, produces in this conductor a current of 1 A, this conductor 
				not being the source of any electromotive force.

Wb.name: weber
Wb.description:
The magnetic flux which, linking a circuit of one turn, produces in it an electromotive force of 1 V 
				as it is reduced to zero at a uniform rate in 1 s.

V.name: volt
V.description:
The difference of electric potential between two points of a conductor carrying a constant current 
				of 1 A when the power dissipated between these points is equal to 1 W.

J.name: joule
J.description:
The work done when the point of application of a force of 1 N is displaced a distance of 1 m in the 
				direction of the force.

Btu[IT].name: British thermal unit
Btu[IT].description:
The amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 pound-mass of water 1 degree Fahrenheit. 
				Uses the International Table (IT) calorie which was defined by the Fifth International Conference on 
				the Properties of Steam (London, July 1956) to be exactly 4.1868 J. 
				In order to convert from calorie to BTU, multiply by the conversion from gram to pound-mass and 
				multiply by the conversion from Celsius interval to Fahrenheit interval. 
				That is, 1 calorie= (1e-3/ 0.45359237)*(1/(5/9)) BTU= (.001*9)/(5*0.45359237) BTU= (9/2.26796185e+3) 
				BTU. 
				Given, cal[IT]=4.1868 J, it follows that Btu[IT] = (4.1868*2.26796185e+3)/9 = 1,055.05585262 J.

Btu[th].name: thermochemical British thermal unit
Btu[th].description:
The amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 pound-mass of water 1 degree Fahrenheit. 
				Based on the thermochemical calorie. 
				In order to convert from calorie to BTU, multiply by the conversion from gram to pound-mass and 
				multiply by the conversion from Celsius interval to Fahrenheit interval. 
				That is, calorie = (1e-3/ 0.45359237)*(1/(5/9)) BTU = (.001*9)/(5*0.45359237) BTU = 
				(9/2.26796185e+3) BTU. 
				Given, cal[th] = 4.184 J, it follows that Btu[th] = (4.184*2.26796185e+3)/9 J = (9.4891523804e+3)/9 
				J which is approximately 1.0543502644888888888888888888889e+3 J.

Btu[UK].name: United Kingdom British thermal unit
Btu[UK].description: The legal unit used in the United Kingdom.

cal[IT].name: calorie [International Table]
cal[IT].description:
This uses the International Table definition. 
				The amount of heat required at a pressure of one atmosphere to raise the temperature of one gram of 
				water one degree Celsius.

cal[th].name: calorie
cal[th].description:
This uses the thermochemical definition. 
				The amount of heat required at a pressure of one atmosphere to raise the temperature of one gram of 
				water one degree Celsius.

erg.name: erg
erg.description: An erg is the amount of work done by a force of one dyne exerted for a distance of one centimeter.

eV.name: electronvolt
eV.description:
The electronvolt is the kinetic energy acquired by an electron in passing through a potential 
				difference of 1 V in vacuum, 1.602 176 487(40) x 10-19 J. 
				This value of 1 eV is the 2006 CODATA recommended value with the standard uncertainty in the last 
				two digits given in parenthesis. 
				From NIST-SI.

quad.name: quad
quad.description: A quad is a unit of energy equal to 1E+15 (international table) BTU.

therm[EC].name: European Community therm
therm[EC].description:
A therm is one hundred thousand BTU (but depends on the definition of BTU). 
				The therm (EC) is legally defined in the Council Directive of 20 December 1979, Council of the 
				European Communities (now the European Union, EU). 
				It is based on the International Table Btu.

therm[UK].name: United Kingdom therm
therm[UK].description: A therm is one hundred thousand BTU (but depends on the definition of BTU).

therm[US].name: United States therm
therm[US].description:
A therm is one hundred thousand BTU (but depends on the definition of BTU). 
				The therm (US) is legally defined in the Federal Register of July 27, 1968. 
				Although the therm (EC), which is based on the International Table Btu, is frequently used by 
				engineers in the United States, the therm (US) is the legal unit used by the U.S. 
				natural gas industry.

lbm.ft2/s2.name: pound-mass square foot per second squared

W.name: watt
W.description: The power that represents a rate of energy transfer of 1 J/s.

hp.name: horsepower
hp.description: The mechanical horsepower, also known as imperial horsepower, of exactly 550 foot pound-force per second.

hp[elec].name: electric-horsepower
hp[elec].description:
The horsepower used for electrical machines is defined as exactly 746 W. 
				Outside the United States watts are generally used for electrical power applications.

hp[hyd].name: hydraulic-horsepower
hp[hyd].description:
Also called water horsepower (from NIST-SI). 
				Commonly calculated with the equation HHP=P*Q/1714, where P stands for pressure in pounds per square 
				inch, Q stands for flow rate in gallons per minute, and 1714 is a conversion factor necessary to 
				yield HHP in terms of horsepower (from Schlumberger Oilfield Glossary).

hp[metric].name: metric-horsepower
hp[metric].description:
The power to raise a mass of 75 kilograms against the earth's gravitational force over a distance of 
				one metre in one second. 
				Also known as the Pferdestarke (PS), the paardenkracht (pk), the cheval vapeur (CV) and the cavallo 
				vapore (cv).

tonRefrig.name: ton-refrigeration
tonRefrig.description: A ton of refrigeration is 12,000 (international table) Btu/h.

bbl.name: barrel
bbl.description:
42 US gallons. 
				1 barrel of oil (bbl) is defined as exactly 42 US liquid gallons. 
				1 US liquid gallon is defined as exactly 231 cubic inches (see NIST-130 reference). 
				1 inch is defined as exactly 0.0254 metres. 
				Therefore, 1 bbl = (42 x 231 x 0.0254**3) m3 = 0.158987294928 m3 exactly. 
				Note that this definition is based in the international inch and NOT the older US survey inch.

floz[UK].name: UK fluid-ounce
floz[UK].description:
United Kingdom 1/20 of UK pint. 
				Therefore, 1/160 of UK gallon or (1/160)* 4.54609 cubic decimetres. 
				From UK-1985.

floz[US].name: US fluid-ounce
floz[US].description: 1/16 of US pint which is 1/8 of US gallon. Therefore, 1/128 of US gallon.

gal[UK].name: UK gallon
gal[UK].description:
United Kingdom Imperial gallon. 
				In Great Britain, a unit of capacity, by the Weights and Measures Act of 1985, exactly "4.54609 
				cubic decimeters".

gal[US].name: US gallon
gal[US].description:
The United States liquid gallon is legally defined as 231 cubic inches, and is equal to exactly 
				3.785411784 litres. 
				Authorized tables, US Code, Title 15, chapter 6, subchapter I, section 205.

L.name: litre
L.description:
Liquid volume. 
				In the US, this is called a liter. 
				By action of the 12th General Conference on Weights and Measures (1964), the liter is a special name 
				for the cubic decimeter.

pt[UK].name: UK pint
pt[UK].description: There are two pints to one quart

pt[US].name: US pint
pt[US].description: There are two pints to one quart

qt[UK].name: UK quart
qt[UK].description: There are four quarts to one gallon.

qt[US].name: US quart
qt[US].description: There are four quarts to one gallon.

ft3.name: cubic foot
ft3.description: The volume of a cube with sides of one foot (0.3048 m) in length

ft3/(ft.psi.d).name: cubic foot per day foot psi

mD.ft2/(lbf.s).name: millidarcy square foot per pound-force second

mD.in2/(lbf.s).name: millidarcy square inch per pound-force second

m4/s.name: metre to the fourth power per second

1000 ft3/(psi.d).name: (thousand cubic foot per day) per psi

J.m/(s.m2.deltaK).name: joule metre per second square metre delta kelvin

Btu[IT].in/(h.ft2.deltaF).name: BTU per (hour square foot delta Fahrenheit per inch)

kJ.m/(h.m2.deltaK).name: kilojoule metre per hour square metre delta kelvin

Btu[IT]/(h.ft.deltaF).name: BTU per hour foot delta Fahrenheit

cal[th]/(h.cm.deltaC).name: calorie per hour centimetre delta Celsius

cal[th]/(s.cm.deltaC).name: calorie per second centimetre delta Celsius

kcal[th]/(h.m.deltaC).name: thousand calorie per hour metre delta Celsius

N.name: newton
N.description: That force which, when applied to a body having a mass of 1 kg, gives it an acceleration of 1 m/s2.

dyne.name: dyne
dyne.description:
A unit of force in the centimetre-gram-second system of physical units, equal to the force that 
				would give a free mass of one gram an acceleration of one centimetre per second per second.

gf.name: gram-force
gf.description:
The gram-force is equal to a mass of one gram multiplied by the standard acceleration due to gravity 
				on Earth, which is defined as exactly 9.80665 meter per second squared.

lbf.name: pound-force
lbf.description:
The pound-force is equal to the gravitational force exerted on a mass of one avoirdupois pound on 
				the surface of Earth. 
				The exact conversion factor is 4.448 221 615 260 5 E+00 since the standard value of the acceleration 
				due to gravity, gn = 9.806 65 m/s2 exactly, is used to define the kilogram-force: 1 kgf = 9.806 65 
				E+00 N exactly.

pdl.name: poundal
pdl.description:
A unit of force equal to the force that would give a free mass of one pound an acceleration of one 
				foot per second per second [i.e., "(lbm.ft)/s2"]. 
				Therefore, 1 pdl = 0.138254954376 N exactly. 
				From merriam-webster.com.

kcal[th].m/cm2.name: thousand calorie metre per square centimetre

cwt[UK].name: UK hundredweight
cwt[UK].description: United Kingdom 112 pound-mass Gross or long hundredweight. From NIST-44.

cwt[US].name: US hundredweight
cwt[US].description: 100 lbm. Net or short hundredweight. From NIST-44.

grain.name: grain
grain.description: The "grain" is the same in avoirdupois, troy, and apothecaries units of mass.

ozm.name: ounce-mass
ozm.description: One sixteenth of an International avoirdupois pound (lbm).

sack[94lbm].name: 94 pound-mass sack
sack[94lbm].description:
A sack with a nominal weight of 94 pound-mass. 
				While the conversion of 94 lbm is exact, the weight of the sack is not exactly 94 lbm.

t.name: tonne
t.description: In the US, this is called a metric ton.

kg.name: kilogram
kg.description:
The kilogram is the unit of mass (not force); it is equal to the mass of the international prototype 
				of the kilogram.

W/(m3.deltaK).name: watt per cubic metre delta kelvin

Btu[IT]/(h.ft3.deltaF).name: BTU per hour cubic foot delta Fahrenheit

Btu[IT]/(s.ft3.deltaF).name: (BTU per second) per cubic foot delta Fahrenheit

kW/(m3.deltaK).name: killowatt per cubic metre delta kelvin

W/(m2.deltaK).name: watt per square metre delta kelvin

Btu[IT]/(h.ft2.deltaF).name: BTU per hour square foot delta Fahrenheit

Btu[IT]/(h.ft2.deltaR).name: BTU per hour square foot delta Rankine

Btu[IT]/(h.m2.deltaC).name: BTU per hour square metre delta Celsius

Btu[IT]/(s.ft2.deltaF).name: (BTU per second) per square foot delta Fahrenheit

cal[th]/(h.cm2.deltaC).name: calorie per hour square centimetre delta Celsius

cal[th]/(s.cm2.deltaC).name: calorie per second square centimetre delta Celsius

J/(s.m2.deltaC).name: joule per second square metre delta Celsius

kcal[th]/(h.m2.deltaC).name: thousand calorie per hour square metre delta Celsius

kJ/(h.m2.deltaK).name: kilojoule per hour square metre delta kelvin

kW/(m2.deltaK).name: kilowatt per square metre delta kelvin

T.name: tesla
T.description:
The magnetic flux density of 1 Wb/m2. 
				Alternatively, it is defined as the magnetic flux density that produces on a 1-m length of wire 
				carrying a current of 1A, oriented normal to the flux density, a force of 1 N, magnetic flux density 
				being defined as an axial vector quantity such that the force exerted on an element of current is 
				equal to the vector product of this element and the magnetic flux density.

gauss.name: gauss
gauss.description:
This unit is part of the so-called electromagnetic three-dimensional CGS system and cannot strictly 
				speaking be compared to the corresponding SI unit, which has four dimensions when only mechanical 
				and electric quantities are considered.

g.ft/(cm3.s).name: gram foot per cubic centimetre second

g.m/(cm3.s).name: gram metre per cubic centimetre second

10 Mg/m3.name: ten thousand kilogram per cubic metre

kg/m4.name: kilogram per metre to the fourth power

g/cm4.name: gram per centimetre to the fourth power

kg/dm4.name: kilogram per decimetre to the fourth power

lbm/ft4.name: pound-mass per foot to the fourth power

Pa.s2/m3.name: pascal second squared per cubic metre

psi2.d/(cP.ft3).name: psi squared day per centipoise cubic foot

P.name: poise
P.description: The poise is the CGS unit for viscosity (also called dynamic viscosity).

kgf.s/m2.name: thousand gram-force second per square metre

Pa.name: pascal
Pa.description: The pressure or stress of 1 N/m2.

at.name: technical atmosphere
at.description:
One technical atmosphere equals one kilogram-force per square centimeter (1 at = 1 kgf/cm2). 
				From NIST.

atm.name: standard atmosphere
atm.description:
An international reference pressure defined as 101.325 kPa and formerly used as unit of pressure. 
				For practical purposes it has been replaced by the bar which is 100 kPa. 
				The difference of about 1% is not significant for many applications, and is within the error range 
				of common pressure gauges.

bar.name: bar
bar.description:
100 kPa. 
				Since 1982 one bar has been used as the standard pressure for tabulating all thermodynamic data. 
				Prior to 1982 the standard pressure used to be the standard atmosphere, equal to 1.013 25 bar, or 
				101 325 Pa.

cmH2O[4degC].name: centimetre of water at 4 degree Celsius
cmH2O[4degC].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

inH2O[39degF].name: inch of water at 39.2 degree Fahrenheit
inH2O[39degF].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

inH2O[60degF].name: inch of water at 60 degree Fahrenheit
inH2O[60degF].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

inHg[32degF].name: inch of mercury at 32 degree Fahrenheit
inHg[32degF].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

inHg[60degF].name: inch of mercury at 60 degree Fahrenheit
inHg[60degF].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

mmHg[0degC].name: millimetres of Mercury at 0 deg C
mmHg[0degC].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

psi.name: pound-force per square inch
psi.description:
Pound-force per square inch. 
				A unit of pressure or of stress based on avoirdupois units. 
				It is the pressure resulting from a force of one pound-force applied to an area of one square inch.

torr.name: torr
torr.description:
The torr is defined as 1/760 of one atmosphere, while the atmosphere is defined as 101.325 kPa. 
				Therefore, 1 Torr is equal to 101325/760 Pa (from Wikipedia).

umHg[0degC].name: micrometre of mercury at 0 degree Celsius
umHg[0degC].description:
NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits 
				are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility 
				of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. 
				Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

kgf.m/cm2.name: thousand gram-force metre per square centimetre

ucal[th]/(s.cm2).name: millionth of calorie per second square centimetre

mol.name: gram-mole
mol.description:
The mole is the amount (in grams) of substance of a system that contains as many elementary entities 
				as there are atoms in 0.012 kilogram of carbon-12. 
				When the mole is used, the elementary entities must be specified and may be atoms, molecules, ions, 
				electrons, other particles, or specified groups of such particles.

lbmol.name: pound-mass-mole
lbmol.description:
The amount (in pound-mass) of substance of a system which contains as many elementary entities as 
				there are atoms in 0.012 kilogram of carbon 12. 
				The conversion involves converting pound-mass to kilograms.

sr.name: steradian
sr.description:
The steradian is the solid angle that, having its vertex in the center of a circle, cuts of an area 
				of the surface of the sphere equal to that of a square with sides of length equal to the radius of 
				the sphere.

s.name: second
s.description:
The second is the duration of 9 192 631 770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition 
				between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the cesium-133 atom.

a.name: julian-year
a.description: The underlying definition taken from NIST statement that "Julian century = 36 525 d".

a[t].name: tropical-year
a[t].description:
The year as a defined multiple of the second that minimizes time-dependent inaccuracy. 
				Used for expressing very long time intervals both for earth scientists and nuclear physicists alike. 
				Takes into account the non-relativistic estimate of astronomical decrease by 0.530 s per century, 
				for the epoch 2000.0. 
				From "International Union of Geological Sciences" (IUPAC Recommendation 2011).

h.name: hour
h.description: One twenty-fourth of a day or 60 minutes.

B.name: bel
B.description:
A unit of intensity. 
				A bel is the base 10 logarithm of a power or amplitude ratio. 
				In using this unit it is important that the nature of the quantity be specified, and that any 
				reference value used be specified.

dAPI.name: API gravity unit
dAPI.description:
A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for gravity of crude petroleum measurements. 
				See the API's Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards (MPMS) chapter 9.1 and chapter 11.1 for 
				information on this concept.

gAPI.name: API gamma ray unit
gAPI.description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for gamma ray log measurements.

nAPI.name: API neutron unit
nAPI.description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for neutron log measurements.

O.name: octave
O.description: The number of octaves between two positive values is the base two logarithm of their ratio.

B/O.name: bel per octave
B/O.description: The power or amplitude variation that occurs over a doubling of the domain variable.

property_kinds.absorbed dose: The amount of energy absorbed per mass.
property_kinds.activity (of radioactivity): A measure of the radiation being emitted.
property_kinds.amplitude: Amplitude of the acoustic signal recorded. It is not a physical property, only a value.
property_kinds.angle per time: The angular velocity. The rate of change of an angle.
property_kinds.area per area: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is area.
property_kinds.attenuation: A logarithmic, fractional change of some measure, generally power or amplitude, over a standard range. This is generally used for frequency attenuation over an octave.
property_kinds.azimuth: Angle between the North and the projection of the normal to the horizon surface estimated on a local area of the interface.
property_kinds.bubble point pressure: The pressure at which the first gas bubble appears while decreasing pressure on a fluid sample.
property_kinds.categorical: The abstract supertype of all enumerated string properties.
property_kinds.cell length: distance from cell face center to cell face center in the specified direction, DI, DJ, DK
property_kinds.continuous: The abstract supertype of all floating point properties.
property_kinds.data transmission speed: used primarily for computer transmission rates.
property_kinds.delta temperature: Delta temperature refers to temperature differences. For non-zero offset temperature scales, Fahrenheit and Celsius, the conversion formulas are different than for absolute temperatures.
property_kinds.depth: The perpendicular measurement downward from a surface. Also, the direct linear measurement from the point of viewing usually from front to back.
property_kinds.dimensionless: A dimensionless quantity is the ratio of two dimensional quantities. The quantity types are not apparent from the basic dimensionless class, but may be apparent in variations - such as area per area, volume per volume, or mass per mass.
property_kinds.dip: In the azimuth direction, Angle between an horizon plane and an estimated plane on a local area of the interface.
property_kinds.discrete: The abstract supertype of all integer properties.
property_kinds.electrochemical equivalent: An electrochemical equivalent differs from molarity in that the valence (oxidation reduction potential) of the element is also considered.
property_kinds.force per force: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is force.
property_kinds.formation volume factor: Ratio of volumes at subsurface and surface conditions
property_kinds.frequency interval: An octave is a doubling of a frquency.
property_kinds.gamma ray API unit: This class is defined by the API, and is used for units of gamma ray log response.
property_kinds.Lambda Rho: Product of Lame constant and density, LR
property_kinds.length per length: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is length.
property_kinds.mass concentration: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is mass.
property_kinds.Mu Rho: Product of Shear modulus and density, MR
property_kinds.net to gross ratio: Ratio of net rock volume to gross rock volume, NTG
property_kinds.pH: The pH is a class that measures the hydrogen ion concentration (acidity).
property_kinds.pore volume: Volume of the Pore Space of the Rock
property_kinds.property multiplier: Unitless multiplier to apply to any property
property_kinds.quantity: The abstract supertype of all floating point properties with a unit of measure.
property_kinds.relative permeability: Ratio of phase permeability, which is a function of saturation, to the rock permeability
property_kinds.relative power: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is power.
property_kinds.relative time: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is time.
property_kinds.RESQML root property: The abstract supertype of all properties. This property does not have a parent.
property_kinds.saturation: Ratio of phase fluid volume to pore volume
property_kinds.solution gas-oil ratio: Ratio of solution gas volume to oil volume at reservoir conditions
property_kinds.thickness: Distance measured in a volume between two surfaces ( e.G. Geological Top Boundary and Geological Bottom Boundary of a Geological unit).
property_kinds.transmissibility: Volumetric flux per unit area per unit pressure drop for unit viscosity fluid
property_kinds.unitless: The abstract supertype of all floating point properties with NO unit of measure. In order to allow the unit information to be required for all continuous properties, the special unit of measure of "NONE" has been assigned to all children of this class. In addition, the special dimensional class of "0" has been assigned to all children of this class.
property_kinds.vapor oil-gas ratio: Ratio of oil vapor volume to gas volume at reservoir conditions
property_kinds.volume per volume: A dimensionless quantity where the basis of the ratio is volume.
